This paper deals with the problem of incorporating knowledge about the learning algorithm and data distribution in the PAC-Bayes framework, which is a popular approach in machine learning. The paper introduces a novel approach to choosing data-dependent priors using differential privacy, which is a topic that falls under the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.IT (Information Theory), and cs.CR (Cryptography). The paper also applies the approach to neural network benchmarks, which falls under the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG, followed by cs.IT, cs.CR, cs.AI, and cs.DS.
